🛒 Retail Oracle V3: Sequential StackTechnical Status: Fully Deployed & OperationalArchitecture: Deep LSTM (V2) Neural EngineObjective: High-Dimensional Time Series ForecastingThis repository features a professional-grade sales forecasting engine developed for the Corporación Favorita grocery datasets. It transforms over 3 million rows of retail data into predictive market intelligence using a deep sequence learning approach.🌐 Live Predictive InterfaceThe forecasting engine is fully deployed. Users can input parameters in a sequential vertical stack to receive real-time sales predictions:⚙️ 10-Step Production PipelineThis project strictly follows the Mastering Data Science 10-step production methodology:Project Definition & Metric: Optimizing for RMSLE ($\sqrt{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n (\log(p_i + 1) - \log(a_i + 1))^2}$) to handle the high variance in grocery sales.Data Ingestion & EDA: Analyzing historical trends across 54 stores using a Macro Trend Blueprint.Data Cleaning: Handling 3M+ rows with zero-null integrity checks.Target Optimization: Applying Logarithmic Transformation (log1p) to stabilize neural network weights, improving the score from ~3.15 to 0.36 RMSLE.Feature Engineering: Decomposing temporal data into Year, Month, Day, and Day of Week artifacts.Categorical Encoding: Utilizing One-Hot Encoding for 33 product families and 54 store locations.Data Scaling & Reshaping: Implementing StandardScaler and 3D reshaping ($[samples, time\_steps, features]$) for the LSTM engine.Model Training: A 5-epoch training sequence using Adam Optimizer and MSE Loss.MLOps Standard: Serialization of the neural brain (store_sales_lstm_v2.h5) with compilation bypass for inference.Cloud Deployment: Seamless integration into a Sequential Stack Streamlit UI on Hugging Face Spaces.🧠 Neural Engine Architecture (V2)The model utilizes a stacked LSTM sequence engine:Layer 1: LSTM (64 units, ReLU, Return Sequences).Layer 2: LSTM (32 units, ReLU).Regularization: Dropout (0.2) to prevent overfitting during high-dimensional learning.Final Output: Dense layer providing a log-transformed prediction, later reversed via expm1.
